  :source-path      "/Users/alfred/code/curator/BOOK/A-branch-scheme-books/cs-curriculum/01-arrays-and-lists.slat"
  :size             5036
  :sha256           "dd3c432958b5ff19"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 01
  :title \"Arrays and Lists — the two simplest sequences\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You are eight years old at a birthday party and there is a line of
   twelve kids waiting to hit a piñata. The order matters. You are
   fourth. Also on the table is a bowl of small paper slips with names
   on them; the mother reaches in to pull one at random for the door
   prize. Both the line and the bowl are collections of things. But
   they are collections in different shapes. The line has a fixed
   order — first, second, third, fourth. The bowl does not. The
   difference between the two shapes is the difference between an
   array (or list) and a set. This chapter is about the first kind.\"

  :what-it-is
  \"An array is a row of boxes in memory, numbered starting from zero.
   Each box holds one thing. To get the thing in box 4, you compute
   the address (start-of-array plus four-box-widths) and read. This
   is fast — one arithmetic step, one memory read.

   A list is a slightly different shape. Instead of a row of boxes at
   consecutive addresses, it is a chain of pairs: (value, next). The
   value is the thing you're holding. The next is a pointer to the
   pair that comes after. To get the fourth item, you have to walk the
   chain: first, second, third, fourth. This is slower than the array
   step, but it has other virtues.\"

  :why-it-exists
  \"Both shapes exist because they solve different problems well. Arrays
   are good when you know how many things you will have, and when you
   want fast index access. Lists are good when you don't know how many
   things you will end up with, when you want to add or remove things
   in the middle without shifting everything, and when the shape of
   the data — recursive, linked, nested — matches the shape of the
   list itself.

   In Scheme, lists are the fundamental collection, because Scheme
   itself is written in lists. Every Scheme program is a list of
   symbols. This turns out to be enormously powerful.\"

  :how-it-works
  \"An array holds N slots. Slot access at position i is O(1) — one
   step regardless of N. Inserting in the middle is O(N) — you have
   to shift everything after the insertion point. Appending at the
   end is amortized O(1) with a dynamic array that doubles its
   capacity.

   A list is made of cons cells. A cons cell is a pair of two things:
   a car (the front of the pair) and a cdr (the rest of the pair).
   The whole list (1 2 3) is the cons cell (1 . (2 . (3 . ()))). The
   () at the end is the empty list, called nil. Access at position
   i is O(i) — you walk the chain. Inserting at the front (cons) is
   O(1). Length is O(N) — you have to walk to count.\"

  :where-in-the-world
  \"Arrays show up as the underlying representation of almost every
   collection in almost every language. Python's list, Java's
   ArrayList, JavaScript's Array — all dynamic arrays under the hood.
   NumPy arrays are contiguous typed memory blocks tuned for speed.

   Lists show up as the fundamental data structure of Lisp-family
   languages (Scheme, Common Lisp, Clojure). They also appear as
   linked lists inside implementations of queues, stacks (though
   arrays are more common), and various graph-representation choices.
   The idea of a list — head plus rest — is the shape of recursion
   itself.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"(define lst '(a b c d))

   (car lst)          ; => a
   (cdr lst)          ; => (b c d)
   (cadr lst)         ; => b  ; (car (cdr lst))
   (caddr lst)        ; => c  ; (car (cdr (cdr lst)))
   (cons 'z lst)      ; => (z a b c d)
   (length lst)       ; => 4

   ; Walk a list
   (define (walk lst)
     (if (null? lst)
         'done
         (begin
           (display (car lst))
           (walk (cdr lst)))))

   ; Length by recursion
   (define (my-length lst)
     (if (null? lst)
         0
         (+ 1 (my-length (cdr lst)))))

   ; Map — apply f to each element
   (define (my-map f lst)
     (if (null? lst)
         '()
         (cons (f (car lst))
               (my-map f (cdr lst)))))

   ; Filter
   (define (my-filter pred lst)
     (cond
       ((null? lst) '())
       ((pred (car lst))
        (cons (car lst) (my-filter pred (cdr lst))))
       (else
        (my-filter pred (cdr lst)))))\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Wittgenstein-early would say: a list is a picture of an ordered
   configuration of things. Its shape shows something a paragraph of
   description doesn't have to say. Peirce would say the position of
   an element in a list is an index — the fifth item is fifth by
   virtue of standing in the fifth relation to the head. Aristotle
   would notice the recursive form — the whole list is head plus
   (a smaller list of the same form). The definition is unified by
   its aim: hold an ordered sequence.

   For the runtime's daily use, the deeper lesson is Quine's. A list is
   a small web of pointers. To understand any node, you need at
   least the head above it. Meaning is holistic even in a list.\")
")
